article.headline: Fourth-quarter surge propels Miami
article.linkText: Heat wear down Wizards for 3rd win in row
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fourth-quarter meltdowns are quickly becoming a thing of the past for the resurgent Miami Heat. Eddie Jones scored 22 points and Rasual Butler added 10 in the fourth quarter as Miami defeated the Washington Wizards 92-84 Friday night for their third straight victory. "I've been happy with the fourth quarters. ... When we play and can take care of the ball, we can be pretty good," Heat coach Stan Van Gundy said. "To be able to do it in the second half shows some maturity." Lamar Odom added 17 points and Dwyane Wade had 15 for the Heat, who have won four of six and seven of nine. Wade sustained a sprained right wrist when he was knocked from behind by Washington's Jared Jeffries in a scrum under the Heat basket with 1:20 remaining. X-rays were negative and Wade, who has scored in double figures for 14 straight games, will be re-evaluated Saturday. "The way we've been playing lately and winning on the road shows that the team has a lot of character," Wade said. Jones shot 9-of-16 from the field and was 4-for-8 from beyond the 3-point arc as the Heat exploited matchups, particularly down the stretch. "I think sometimes when I have do have the ball and the shot's going for me, you still have to be aware of setting the table for the other guys," said Jones, who had a season-high eight assists. "That was my objective tonight. If they didn't show on me well enough, I was going to make them pay." Larry Hughes led the Wizards with 21 points. Washington, which fell to 0-8 against Atlantic Division teams, has dropped three straight and 11 of 14. Jarvis Hayes added 14 points. Washington didn't score from the field after taking a 78-74 lead on Brendan Haywood's three-point play with 7:37 left in the fourth. Haywood finished with 13 points and 11 rebounds. "That's something we've got to look at -- why we couldn't put it in," said Wizards guard Steve Blake. "I don't know if it's good defense or what, but we've got to correct it." After Brevin Knight hit two free throws for an 80-78 lead with 4:52 left, Miami regained the lead on Butler's 3-pointer. Etan Thomas hit two foul shots to put Washington ahead with 4:11 to go, but Brian Grant's jumper started an 11-2 game-closing run. The Heat led 47-44 at halftime and used a 6-0 run late in the first half to erase a 42-41 Washington lead. Odom scored 11 consecutive points for Miami in the third quarter, and Jones followed with a 3-pointer from deep in the right corner for a 63-55 lead with 5:20 left. But the Heat then went 3:20 without hitting a shot from the field, and Hughes' 3 with 26.4 seconds remaining produced a 67-67 tie.

Game notes
Washington activated G Mitchell Butler from the injured list before the game. Butler had missed five games with right knee tendinitis. ... When Blake drew his third foul late in the first quarter, Knight was quickly summoned. Knight played the final 39 seconds with his right shoe unlaced. ... Blake's five assists was a season high. ... Miami, 3-0 versus the Wizards, can sweep the season series for the fourth time in six years by beating Washington on March 21 at MCI Center.
